### Callout Quotes

> **Tip:** Use blockquotes for important notes and tips.
> They stand out from regular text and draw attention.

> **Warning:** This feature is experimental.
> Use at your own risk in production environments.{color=orange border=1px solid orange padding=0 10px}

> **Note:** Remember to save your work before leaving.
> Auto-save is enabled every 5 minutes.{background=light-blue}

### Code Citations

> The `print()` function outputs text to the console.
> It's one of the most commonly used functions in programming.

```python
print("Hello, World!")
```

> Always escape user input before rendering.
> This prevents security vulnerabilities like XSS.

### Multiline Quotes with Formatting

> **Key Principles:**
>
> 1. Keep it simple
> 2. Make it clear
> 3. Be consistent
>
> These three principles will guide your documentation writing process.

### Stylized Quotes

> **Pro Tip:** Use the `&` symbol for technical indentation instead of blockquotes when you need code-like formatting without semantic quoting.

> **Important:** Blockquotes (`>`) are for semantic quotations and callouts.
> Use `&` for technical code blocks or terminal output.

### Quote with Lists

> **Recommended workflow:**
>
> - Write your content first
> - Review and edit
> - Add formatting
> - Test the output
>
> This ensures quality documentation.

